For this stack, I'd keep the MVP very small while still exercising **every technology**.

## MVP: Pizza Order Tracking

The user doesn't log in. They simply place an order and watch it progress in real time.

### Workflow

```text
Customer
    │
    ▼
Choose Products
    │
    ▼
Create Order
    │
    ▼
PENDING
    │
    ▼
PREPARING
    │
    ▼
READY
    │
    ▼
OUT_FOR_DELIVERY
    │
    ▼
DELIVERED
```

Every status change:

* Updates PostgreSQL
* Publishes a Kafka event
* Is consumed by the Notification Service
* Sends a WebSocket update to the browser

This demonstrates the complete event-driven architecture.

---

# Frontend (Next.js)

### Products Page

```
🍕 Margherita
€12

🍔 Burger
€10

🥤 Cola
€3

[Add]
```

---

### Cart

```
Margherita x2

Cola x1

Total €27

[Place Order]
```

---

### Order Tracking

```
Order #42

🟢 Pending

⬜ Preparing

⬜ Ready

⬜ Delivery

⬜ Delivered
```

As WebSocket messages arrive, the UI updates automatically.

---

### Orders

```
POST /orders

GET /orders

GET /orders/:id

PATCH /orders/:id/status
```

---

# Kafka

## Producer

After creating an order:

```
POST /orders

↓

Kafka

↓

order.created
```

---

## Kitchen Service

Consumes

```
order.created
```

Produces

```
order.preparing
```

Later

```
order.ready
```

---

## Delivery Service

Consumes

```
order.ready
```

Produces

```
delivery.started

order.delivered
```

---

## Notification Service

Consumes every event.

```
order.created

order.preparing

order.ready

delivery.started

order.delivered
```

Then

```
WebSocket

↓

Browser
```

---

# WebSocket

Frontend subscribes:

```
order:update
```

Receives:

```json
{
  "orderId": 42,
  "status": "READY"
}
```

The UI updates instantly without refreshing.

---

# PostgreSQL

Just three tables are enough:

```
products

orders

order_items
```

No users.

No authentication.

No payments.

---

